						<summary>

						<p>This is an incomplete inscription beginning with a Sanskrit verse which states that this is an edict of Gaṅga-bhūpa. In the Tamil portion that follows mention is made of this chief under the name <hi rend="bold">Gaṇḍapeṇḍāra Gaṅgayya-Sāhiṇi</hi> and of another person Sāraṅga-Nāyaka. Gaṅgaya Sāhiṇi was a subordinate under Kākatīya king Gaṇapati and was ‘ruling the whole country from Pānuṅgallu to Mārjavāḍa’ (No. 306 of 1931). The inscription is dated in Sādhāraṇa, Karkaṭaka, śu. 12, Monday, Jyēshṭhā which should correspond to A.D. 1250.</p>						

						</summary>
